<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-631-526  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 631 526.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Sept 11 1989 v6 n36 p31(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Financial firms team up in disaster recovery plan: rivals ally torestore voice service in an emergency.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eckerson, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The four financial service firms that make up the MutualAssistance Pact association agree to work together in the event ofan equipment outage at any one of the firms.andP;  The firms, whichinclude Dain Bosworth, First National Bank of Minneapolis, IDSFinancial Corp and Piper, Jaffray and Hopwood, have jointly leasedtelecommunications equipment that would be used in such anemergency and periodically test the disaster recovery procedure.andO;The competing firms depend upon their phones to conduct most oftheir business, and have agreed that if one firm loses phoneservice for an extended period they will share excess capacity.andO;Each firm reserves capacity on its switch to support 300additional phone lines to be used when an outage lasting at leasteight hours occurs.andP;  The plan has existed for four years, but hasnever been implemented in a real-life situation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dain Bosworth Inc. (communication systems)First Bank N.A. (Minneapolis, Minnesota) (communication systems)IDS-Financial Services Inc. (communication systems)Piper, Jaffray and Hopwood Inc. (communication systems).andO;Topic:     Disaster RecoveryStrategic PlanningCooperative AgreementFinancial ServicesTelecommunicationsProfessional AssociationsPBX.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>